<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06178288 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06178288 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: The Nuclear Whales Saxophone Quartet will present &quot;Thar TheyBlow&quot; on Saturday. &quot;We explain a bit about the history of the music as well asthe saxophone,&quot; says leader Don Stevens.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  SUMMER; FAMILY; ENTERTAINMENT; PROGRAM; LIST; SAN-JOSE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  For the next nine Saturdays, local artists that generally perform in areaschools will be performing for the community.;    &quot;The artists are excitedabout performing for children and their parents, an opportunity they don't getin school settings,&quot; said Andrew Bales, planning and development director forthe city of San Jose's Convention and Cultural Affairs Department.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  East Extra  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  S.J. PLANS A WHALE OF A TIME FOR ALL  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Also ran in EX4/5Additional information attached to the end of this article  </MEMO><TEXT>     The Family Series is part of Summer at The Stage, a festival of the artsthat opened last weekend at The Stage theater in downtown San Jose.;    ThisSaturday's offering is &quot;Thar They Blow.&quot;;    &quot;It's a real fun show. Most kidshave not heard a saxophone in this format. The music will appeal to parents asmuch as the kids,&quot; said leader Don Stevens, of The Nuclear Whales SaxophoneQuartet's upcoming performance.;    &quot;We present all styles of music, ragtime,jazz, classical and pop,&quot; said Stevens. &quot;We explain a bit about the history ofthe music as well as the saxophone.&quot;;    The Nuclear Whales are about to starttheir first national tour this summer, promoting their third album, &quot;Thar TheyBlow,&quot; released just this week. Their Saturday concert gives families a chanceto see and hear close-to-home what Stevens described as &quot;very inspiringmusic.&quot;;    Offering a different musical experience is Eth-No-Tec's &quot;BambooJamboo.&quot; Tales from Asia are told theatrically with music and movement in thisunique July 6 event that uses taped synthesized music, blended with liveJapanese Taiko drums, Filipino Kulintang gongs and Chinese Ditza flute.;   Venturing to another part of the globe, audiences can see Mazad Galindo, whoplays more than 100 ancient instruments, will create original music usingpre-Columbian instruments of the Aztec, Mayan and other Meso-Americancivilizations in this July 13 performance.;    On July 20, Fun City ShowCompany will present &quot;Folktales and Fun from Around the World.&quot;;    &quot;We arestory theater in the truest sense of the word. We use all of the performingarts to make the stories we choose come alive -- music, mime, comedy, drama,even circus skills,&quot; said Robin Stevens, director of the Fun City ShowCompany.;    On Aug. 10, Fun City brings favorite stories to life in&quot;Fantastic Classics.&quot;;    Other performances in this series include:;   (check) &quot;Imagine If&quot; presented by Tandy Beal andamp; Company on July 27. The danceperformance uses rhythm, shape, motion, props, music and illusion.;    (check)&quot;Fiesta Mexicana,&quot; 34 talented dancers and musicians of the Aztlan Academywill showcase the folklore of Mexico on Aug. 3.;    (check) The 500thanniversary of the exploration of America is the theme for a specialperformance by the Flamenco Society of San Jose on Aug. 17.;    &quot;We will showhow the heels of the flamenco dancer are used as a percussion instrument andwill show the other forms of percussion, the castanets and palmas --hand-clapping,&quot; said Anita Sheer, artistic director. &quot;The children will thenhave the chance to try hand-clapping and to sing a little bit.&quot;;    (check)The Theatre of All Possibilities closes the Family Series on Aug. 24, with itsmusical, &quot;The Best Possible Me,&quot; which carries an important message aboutself-esteem.;  FAMILY SERIES EVENTS; Following is a schedule of one-hourperformances in the Family Series, a part of Summer at The Stage at 490 S.First St., San Jose. Tickets for the Family Series are $4 each. For ticketscall, (408) 283-7142, Tuesday through Saturday, noon to 5 p.m.; (box)June 29-- &quot;Thar They Blow,&quot; Nuclear Whales Saxophone Quartet.; (box)July 6 --&quot;Ceremonial Native American Music&quot; with Mazatl Galindo.; (box)July 20 --&quot;Folktales and Fun from Around the World,&quot; Fun City Show Company.; (box)July27 -- &quot;Imagine If,&quot; Tandy Beal andamp; Company.; (box)Aug. 3 -- &quot;Fiesta Mexicana,&quot;Aztlan Academy.; (box)Aug. 10 -- &quot;Fantastic Classics,&quot; Fun City Show Company.;(box)Aug. 17 -- &quot;The Nina, the Pinta, andamp; the Santa Maria,&quot; Flamenco Society ofSan Jose.; (box)Aug. 24 -- &quot;The Best Possible Me,&quot; Theatre of AllPossibilities.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  KATHERINE THORNBERRY, Special to the Mercury News  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910626  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  688  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday June 26, 199100178288,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>